The Grasshopper Years of Latin America.
The bad news continues to pile up these days in Latin America.
The economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It's hardly surprising since the great majority of Latin America countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
The capital has been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
The Grasshopper Years have really been consumed by the Grasshoppers.
Over the past twenty years, the annual growth rate of per capita GDP in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With a growth rate so anemic, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through a timid rise in wages at best?
The economic stagnation is due to poor governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush to privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, was sold off at auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues generated from privatization have yielded little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Even worse, the liquidation of state assets has been accompanied by a massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing done by the national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in nearly all countries in Latin America.
Secondly, given that reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disenchanted.
The influx of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing freely, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would embark on another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
Without a more substantial number of deep reforms, too few conditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma foretells the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that functioned along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, inept presidents succeed one another.
The institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being challenged, and a haphazard and even more corrupt effort at redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela are hardly any better off, and Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who are leading the opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, suggests that a significant portion of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far removed from the dominant economic thought and politics that capital has already begun to flee - even though the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but it may yet prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance continues to deteriorate, the economy risks a hard landing.
Regarding all the good news about Mexico's emerging democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it's doing.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, that is the economically speaking financial outcome, as where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis to accumulate capital and boost productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the oil-rich years of the 1970s OPEC, to which it did not belong, having neglected to develop its own oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina now takes a vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates almost reach 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are market-friendly and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and adaptable in its learning.
Rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
His GDP per capita is only half that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate of around 15% per year in China's coastal region, can anyone seriously doubt that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to go smoothly, primarily due to the massive influx of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of accession to the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments are backtracking on reform and the economy is losing ground relative to the rest of the world.
Latin America prospered when unregulated funds flowed in, but those times are largely behind us.
We can therefore expect significantly worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem - once again a presidential candidate in Argentina - may seem like a bad joke, but anyone concerned with the fate of Latin America should not be laughing.
